#Text=Santa Cruz ( California )

#Text=Santa Cruz is a small coastal city ( population about 55,000 ) in Santa Cruz County , at the north end of Monterey Bay in California , about 40 miles ( 64 km ) south of San Jose and 75 miles ( 120 km ) south of San Francisco .
#Text=Understand

#Text=Santa Cruz is best known as a countercultural hub , with a bohemian feel and youthful vibe , and fun weekend tourist attractions like the Santa Cruz Beach Boardwalk and the dubious Mystery Spot .
#Text=The rather relaxed beach lifestyle is supplemented by some remaining high tech industry and a vibrant university culture .

#Text=The University of California Santa Cruz ( UCSC ) is regarded as one of the premier centers of higher learning in the region and was once well known for its strong emphasis on the arts and humanities .
#Text=The beaches north and south of Santa Cruz are considered some of the more pristine areas of natural beauty in central California .
#Text=A variety of conditions prevail , depending on the beach , few are suited for swimming due to temperature and current , several are considered an expert surfer 's cold cold paradise .

#Text=Do n't expect a beach culture like Southern California , with bikini babes and children swimming in the surf ; for much of the year it 's considered perfectly normal to wear a sweater and long pants to the beach .
#Text=The beautiful beaches and the rather mild climate play a central role in local culture .
#Text=Most visitors leave Santa Cruz amazed by the city 's beauty and ambiance .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Highway 17 south from San Jose is the most direct route when driving from the more populated parts of the Bay Area .
#Text=It is a winding and very dangerous road over the mountains , arguably the most hazardous in the state shared during the week with heavy gravel trucks , so heed the speed limits
#Text=take it easy and arrive alive .
#Text=Accidents are very common , but the road is a bit safer since the addition of concrete barriers some years ago .
#Text=Beware of fog , as well as " hurried " drivers , and drive with caution , especially when roads are wet .
#Text=To merge from Highway 17 to Highway 1 in Santa Cruz
#Text=to continue south , you must merge three times on the dreaded " fish hook " .
#Text=This causes the beginning of the dreaded commute from " over the hill " to the coast for many .
#Text=Congestion usually lasts M - F 3PM until 6PM , from just south of 41st Ave. on Highway 1 , spilling back onto Highway 17 going south .

#Text=Highway 9 is a a slower , longer , and more scenic route over the mountains , but it can get congested , and is often subject to extended periods of closure due to landslide damage during the winter .
#Text=It 's also very popular with both bicyclists and motorcyclists , so if driving a car over it be sure to be vigilant .

#Text=A much more beautiful , but slower , approach to Santa Cruz is on Highway 1 , either from the north , San Francisco and Pacifica ( about 65 miles ) , or from the south , Monterey and Big Sur ( about 35 miles ) .
#Text=During stormy seasons , check for rare , but often long-term road closures , although Devil 's Slide , the most notorious location for landslides , was bypassed by a tunnel several years ago .

#Text=To take public transportation there is a commuter shuttle , the Highway 17 Express ( Santa Cruz route 17 ; VTA route 970 ; Amtrak Thruway Motorcoach Rt 17 ) , that runs from Diridon Station , in San Jose 7 days a week with connections to Amtrak Capitol Corridor , CalTrain , Altmont Corridor Express and other Amtrak trains serving San Jose .
#Text=There are also multiple lines that go south to Watsonville 7 days a week .
#Text=Greyhound also runs buses to the city .
#Text=All these lines go to , or near to , the Santa Cruz Metro Center , which is in the downtown area .
#Text=The nearest major airport is in San Jose ( SJC ) , but San Francisco International Airport ( SFO ) and even Oakland ( OAK ) are n't much farther away , and sometimes have cheaper flights .

#Text=The small regional airport in Monterey ( MRY ) has flights to major hubs ( Los Angeles , San Francisco , Sacramento ) , but in most cases San Jose is the best choice because of the greater choice of airlines and destinations .
#Text=Scheduled airport shuttles provide service every few hours to San Jose , and less often to San Francisco .
#Text=Caltrain also provides a route to the San Francisco airport , through a transfer with BART in Millbrae .
#Text=For private aircraft , there'a 2,000 ft. runway about 10 miles northwest of downtown , near Henry Cowell Redwoods State Park .
#Text=Get around
#Text=The main downtown strip is pedestrian friendly , and it 's a 20-minute stroll from there to the beach .
#Text=Walking to the University of California Santa Cruz from downtown is a little more difficult , with bad or non-existent sidewalks and a very steep climb .
#Text=While driving is certainly an option ( parking is tight , careful to not get ticketed ) , Santa Cruz Metro provides bus service .
#Text=Santa Cruz can be a wonderful town for town for cycling , but be careful because drivers are no better here than in many other places .
#Text=Around town and along Highway 1 is easy , but roads in the Santa Cruz Mountains are steep , winding and challenging for many cyclists .
#Text=Be careful .
#Text=Collisions between bicycles and cars are often reported .
#Text=A number of pedestrian and car collisions have also happened in the downtown area .
#Text=See
#Text=Mission Santa Cruz , 126 High St , ☏ +1831 425-5849 .
#Text=Th - Sa 10AM to 4PM ( & Su during the summer ) ; closed holidays .
#Text=The original Mission Santa Cruz was dedicated by Fermin Lasuen in 1791 as the 12th California mission .
#Text=In its early years , the mission suffered due to violence among the Indians .
#Text=The original mission buildings ( save one ) fell down in an 1857 earthquake , and it is place was built a Catholic Church with the anglicized name Holy Cross Church .
#Text=However , a replica of the old mission was constructed nearby at half-scale in the 1930s by a wealthy benefactor .
#Text=This exists today as Santa Cruz Mission State Historic Park .
#Text=Free .
#Text=The Beach Boardwalk , 400 Beach St. 11AM to 10 or 11PM .
#Text=Founded in 1907 , it is the only original boardwalk amusement park still operating on the West Coast .
#Text=It features one of the oldest wooden rollercoasters still in use in the US as well as numerous modern attractions .
#Text=Entrance is free , rides cost between $ 2 – 4 each ( but less than $ 1 on selected summer evenings ) .
#Text=Day , month , and yearly passes available .
#Text=Municipal Wharf , 21 Municipal Wharf .
#Text=Restaurants , gift shops , sea lions and pelicans , and great views .
#Text=Mystery Spot , 465 Mystery Spot Rd ( 3 miles north of town ; take Water St , then Market St , then Branciforte Drive ) .
#Text=The famous ( ' as seen on TV ' ) tourist trap , complete with anti-gravity cabin and amazing hillside of illusion .
#Text=$ 6 ; $ 5 at the door .
#Text=Surfing Museum , 701 W Cliff Dr ( in the lighthouse at Lighthouse Point ) .
#Text=Th - M noon-4PM .
#Text=Memorabilia from the introduction of surfing to California by Hawaiians in 1885 to the present day .
#Text=A statue of an early surfer is a few yards from the museum .
#Text=Free .
#Text=Seymour Marine Discovery Center , 100 Shaffer Rd .
#Text=End of Delaware Ave. Tu - Sa 10AM-5PM , Su noon-5PM .
#Text=Has exhibits focusing on ocean conservation and marine science , big tanks full of native species , a guided tour with a dolphin overlook area , and amazing views of Monterey Bay at sunset .
#Text=$ 6 .
#Text=University of California at Santa Cruz ( UCSC ) ( On the hill at the north end of town ) .
#Text=This UC campus has a smaller student population ( except for the brand new campus in Merced ) , with about 15,000 students .
#Text=The main part of campus is spread over half of 2001 acres ( 8.1 km ² ) , mostly covered with redwood forests with the occasional stunning view of the bay .
#Text=There is an UCSC Arboretum specializing in native plants and plants from Australia .

#Text=Mountain bike and hiking trails criss-cross the upper part of campus , connecting Wilder Ranch State Park to Henry Cowell Redwoods State Park ( get a trail map and a parking permit from the kiosk as you enter campus ) .
#Text=The Bay Tree Bookstore sells clothes with the UCSC mascot – the banana slug .
#Text=The critters themselves are fairly common in the surrounding redwood forest - their bright yellow color tells would-be predators that their skin secretes a foul-tasting poison .
#Text=Keep your eyes open for mountain lions seen ( but rarely ) in undeveloped parts of the campus .
#Text=Downtown Santa Cruz .
#Text=Lots to see and do here all day and night ; " SantaCruz " character mixed with some great restaurants and lots of cool shops .
#Text=Mostly it 's a great people watching center .
#Text=The nightlife is worth sticking around for .
#Text=Pacific Ave is the main street downtown .
